CatDescriptText: Cutline of image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, January 17, 1959, pg. 3 reads: "Brown and Conlon Residences - The three-story building, left, at 534 Brushton Ave., in which Dr. James E. Brown spent his last years. The stone building, owned by the bachelor physician, houses three apartments.  Dr. Brown lived on the ground floor, with Raymond Jones, a long-time friend and companion, occupying the second-floor apartment...."
TitMainTitle: Three story stone and brick house with mansard roof, owned by Dr. James E. Brown, at 534 Brushton Avenue
